text: EurJOC European Journal of Organic Chemistry In Situ Generation of Allenes and their Application to One-Pot Assembly of Functionalized Fluoreno[3,2-b]furans by Calcium- Catalyzed, Regioselective, 3-Component Reactions Srinivasarao Yaragorla*[a] and Pallava Rajesh[a] Abstract: We have developed a novel synthetic methodology tetra-annulated fluorenofurans and for fluorenopyrans using calcium(II)-catalyzed one-pot, three-com- ponent reaction. Fluorene moiety is often found in many of the biologically ac- tive natural products and drug candidates,[1] it served as a po- tential building block for the synthesis of molecules that display advanced materials applications.[2] Further, fluorenes fused with arenes or heteroarenes are known to exhibit interesting optoelectronic properties due to the presence of extended π-conjugation.[3] Among these fused-fluorenes (Figure 1), the synthesis of benzofluorenes has been well explored due to their importance. For example, fluostatin family of natural critical products exhibit dipeptidyl peptidases inhibition, antibacterial and antitumor activities.[4] Kinamycin natural products possess antibiotic and cytotoxic activities,[5] they serve as nonsteroidal drug candidates for the estrogen receptor-related treatments,[6] they were used as synthetic precursors[7] and also used in func- tional materials with promising applications.[8] Therefore, the development of the new synthetic methods for the construc- tion of benzofluorenes and their derivatives becomes an active research area.[9–14] Some of the notable synthetic methods are cycloaromatization of non-conjugated benzotriynes reported by Dominguez and Saà,[9] another method on intramolecular [4+2] cycloaddition of diaryl-acetylenes by the same group.[10] Further, an intramolecular arylalkyne–allene cycloaddition re- ported by Echavarren,[11] selenium-mediated carbo-cyclization of stilbene derivatives by Wirth,[12] and iron(III)chloride cata- lyzed tandem Conia–ene/Friedel–Crafts annulation of o-alkyn- yldihydrochalcones by Srinivasan's group were also reported.[13] [a] Dr. S. Broad substrate scope, regioselectivity, gram-scale syn- thesis, and benzylic functionalization of products are some of the highlights of this protocol. On the other hand, propargyl alcohols are one of the key build- the synthesis of various heterocyclic com- ing blocks for pounds.[15] Besides, propargyl alcohols can undergo a variety of cascade transformations, cycloisomerization via regioselective exo- or endo-pathway to yield the desired products with maxi- mum atom economy. Hence, few research groups had developed the fused-fluor- enes from propargyl alcohols. To list a few, Liang group re- ported a palladium-catalyzed bicyclization of propargylic com- pounds with terminal alkynes to afford benzo[b]fluorenes (Scheme 1, equation-i).[16] Liu group reported gold-catalyzed cyclizations of 1,6-diynyl carbonates to form benzo[b]fluorenes via arylation of oxocarbenium ion intermediates followed by decarboxylative etherification (Scheme 1, equation-ii).[17] The importance of these products prompted us to develop a calcium-catalyzed fluorenopyran (inserting oxygen atom into the benzofluorene) synthesis from tert-propargyl alcohols and 1,3-diketone (Scheme 1, equation-iii).[18] Notably, all these methods involved the fusion of a six-membered ring to the EurJOC European Journal of Organic Chemistry Scheme 1. Later, Chen group reported an in- teresting example of thiophene-fused fluorene (Scheme 1, equation-iv);[19] however, this reaction limited to the single ex- ample as their primary focus is on benzofluorene synthesis. Moreover, thiophene ring fused to fluorene in the product was originated from the starting material (Scheme 1, equation-iv). Although the handful of synthetic methods have been reported for the benzofluorenes, the fusion of five-membered arenes (6–5–6–5 scaffolds), particularly hetero arenes such as a furan is not yet known.

Recently, we have demonstrated the annulation reaction of propargyl alcohols with 1,3-diketones to synthesize functional- ized fluorenes[20] and indeno[2,1-g]chromenes having 6–5–6–6 core structure.[18] With this experience, we sought to explore the possibility to develop a one-pot regiodivergent synthesis of functionalized fluoreno[3,2-b]furans having 6–5–6–5 core struc- ture, from the annulation of in situ generated allenes and prop- argyl alcohols.[21] The Schematic illustration of this is described in Scheme 2. As we have evidenced, in situ generated allene-A from propargyl alcohol 1 and diketone 2 in the presence of calcium-catalyst is the key intermediate in this annulation. This allene was further undergone cycloisomerization to yield fluorenol B and reacted with tert-propargyl alcohol to form ether C, via hard-hard reactivity. This ether was then undergone a thermal rearrangement to yield the indenochromene D via a 6-endo-cyclization.[18] Further investigations on exploring the strength and scope of this protocol to form a 6–5–6–5 core structure, we need to alter the reaction path after the formation of fluorenol-B. Since these structural motifs have highly pre- EurJOC European Journal of Organic Chemistry

vailed in material applications, it would be appropriate to de- tour the reaction mechanism to 5-exo-cyclization mode to ob- tain a furan ring fused to fluorene (compound-F). For that, we need to form a carbon-carbon bond unlike carbon-oxygen bond with B. Which shall be possible, if we add sec-propargyl alcohol to fluorenol-B to give intermediate E. Again at this stage, phenolic-OH can cyclize with the alkyne in two paths, either a 5-exo-dig-pathway to furnish fluorenofuran-F, or a 6-endo-dig-pathway to yield fluorenopyran-G. The regioselecti- vity of the cyclization shall merely be controlled by having a suitable substitution on the alkyne, that is R2-group. To check the feasibility of our hypothesis (Scheme 2), we com- menced the annulation reaction by choosing the 1,1,3-triphen- ylprop-2-yn-1-ol (1a), 3-methylpentane-2,4-dione (2a), 1,3-di- phenylprop-2-yn-1-ol (3a) as the reacting partners. Initially, a mixture of 1a (0.35 mol), 2a (0.45 mmol) and 10/10 mol-% of Ca(OTf )2/Bu4NPF6 was refluxed in 1,2-dichloroethane until the complete formation of fluorenol 4aa[20] (monitored by TLC) and was added 0.42 mmol of sec-propargyl alcohol 3a to the reac- tion and continued to reflux for 12 hours (entry 1, Table 1). As predicted, the reaction yielded the desired tetracyclic fluoreno- [3,2-b]furan 4a,[22] but in poor yield (10 %), luckily the rest of the product – was characterized as 4aa′, which was proposed as the key intermediate for the formation of 4a. decided to introduce a base to accelerate the cyclization of 4aa′ to 4a.[23] Accordingly, after the formation of 4aa′ (as mentioned in entry 1), DABCO (1 equiv.) was added to the reaction, and the reflux was continued for 12 hours, which resulted in a moderate increase of reaction yield (entry 2) along with unreactive 4aa′. Interestingly, the addition of the excess base (DABCO) into the reaction has a remarkable increment in the reaction yield (en- tries 3,4). Then the search for finding better solvent systems (acetonitrile, toluene and tetrahydrofuran) for this transforma- tion did not give us satisfactory results (entries 5–7). While look- ing at the mixed solvents, we found that the combination of DCE/CH3CN (1:1) as the best solvent system to yield 4a in 80 % (entries 8, 9). Next, we explored the possibility of minimizing the catalyst loadings (entries 10, 11) and found that 10/5 mol- % of Ca(II)/Bu4NPF6 gave the best reaction yield. As presumed the reaction furnished only 48 % of 4a without the additive (entry 12), because there exists a ligand metathesis between Ca(OTf )2 and Bu4NPF6 to form more active catalyst Ca(OTf )(PF6). The use of KPF6 as an alternative additive with Ca(II) combina- tion was not effective (entry 13), which indicates the impor- tance of Bu4N+ as the counterion over K+. The search for alter- native bases such as DBU, potassium carbonate, and sodium carbonate to promote the complete cyclization of 4aa′ to 4a were not successful (entries, 14–16). We have also explored other catalysts such as magnesium triflate (entry 17), ferric chloride (entry 18) and para-toluenesulfonic acid (entry 19) to promote the annulation reaction of 1a, 2a, and 3a, but none of them showed the better reactivity. Based on the previous results obtained by us, and other re- search groups,[18,20,25] we proposed the possible reaction mech- anism for this annulation reaction in Scheme 10. The reaction initiated by SN2 substitution reaction between compounds 1 and 2, to furnish the tetrasubstituted allene intermediate A (iso- lated). Subsequent intramolecular-allene-Friedel-Crafts-Annula- tion reaction (I-AFCA) of A results the tricyclic compound B, which readily isomerizes to indene C. Compounds C and D ex- ists in keto-enol tautomerism, and undergo a calcium-catalyzed intramolecular-aldol reaction to give tri-carbocyclic compound E, which undergo elimination (F) and aromatization to produce fluorenol G (isolated). Calcium-catalyzed, C–C bond formation between G and 3 provides intermediate H (isolated). Here the cyclization mode was defined based on the nature of the R1-group. If R1 is aryl group (Case 1), DABCO assisted Ca(II) in- creases the acidity the phenolic proton, which is in close prox- imity and allows protonation of alkyne through a tight six- membered transition state (I) to furnish the cationic compound J. At this stage, the bond rotation is restricted by the steric- DABCO ligands attached to calcium, and hence the cation (J) isomerizes to K and thus facilitates the formation of furan ring L, which finally aromatizes to give compound 4. In case-2, where R1 is ester group (M), the Lewis acidity of calcium induces the charge separation on propargyl ester (N), and thus it readily undergoes intramolecular Oxa-Michael addition to yield com- pound 6, via the intermediates O, P. In case 3, if R1 is an alkyl group (Q), again the acidity of the phenolic proton increases by the calcium and protonates the alkyne due to the close proxim- ity through a six-membered transition state to form the cation R. The C–C bond rotation provides the proper orientation (S, the positive charge is stabilized by the +I effect of the alkyl

The C–C bond rotation provides the proper orientation (S, the positive charge is stabilized by the +I effect of the alkyl groups) for cyclization to yield the pyran 8. (Scheme 10).

[b] Emission wavelengths at room temperature (25 °C) in chloroform at a concentration of (1 × 10–4 M). organic light-emitting-diodes and biological labeling applica- tions.[27] In conclusion, we have succeeded in showing a calcium-cata- lyzed, cascade and highly regioselective sequential annulation reaction to furnish functionalized fluoreno[3,2-b]furans and indeno[2,1-g]chromenes. This protocol offers a one-pot, three- component reaction to form structurally complex tetra-annu- lated hetero-aryls, where five C–C bonds and one C–O bond formation occurred. The scope of substitutions on aryl rings is well explored, and the role of sec-propargyl alcohol in determin- ing the regioselectivity is extensively studied and confirmed as the crucial. The cyclization reaction with sec-propargyl alcohols requires the base only if the alkyne terminus is the aryl-substi- tuted; in case of, ester or alkyl group, the reaction completes without the aid of base. Further, the gram-scale synthesis and synthetic transformations of the products through Csp3-H func- tionalization is demonstrated. Isolation of critical intermediates during the progress of the reaction helped us to propose the reaction mechanism.

Unless otherwise noted, all reagents were used as received from commercial suppliers. All reactions were performed in flame-dried or oven-dried glassware with magnetic stirring and were monitored using thin-layer chromatography (TLC) with aluminium sheets silica gel 60 F-254 from Merck. TLC plates were visualized with UV light (25 nm), iodine treatment or using p-anisaldehyde or KMnO4 stain. Column chromatography was carried out using silica gel 60– 120 mesh as the stationary phase. NMR spectra were recorded at 500 MHz and 400 MHz (1H-NMR), and 13C{1H} NMR recorded using 125 MHz and 100 MHz on Avance Bruker spectrometer. Chemical shifts (δ) are reported in ppm, using the residual solvent peak in CDCl3 (1H: δ= 7.26 and 13C: δ = 77.16 ppm) as an internal standard. The coupling constants (J) are given in Hz. HRMS were recorded using ESI-TOF techniques. Melting points were measured with LABINDIA melting apparatus. General experimental procedure for the synthesis of tert-prop- argylic alcohol (1): A mixture of the terminal alkyne (1.2 equiv.), tBuOK (1.5 equiv.) and ketone (1 equiv.) was stirred in a reaction flask at room temperature under nitrogen atmosphere for 2–6 h. After completion of the reaction (monitored by TLC), the reaction was quenched with water and extracted into ethyl acetate (thrice). The combined organic layers were washed with brine solution, dried with anhydrous Na2SO4. The organic solvent was removed under reduced pressure to obtain the tert-propargyl alcohols 1 as a pure compound. Eur. J. Org. I. Experimental procedure for the synthesis of (4a): A mixture of tert-propargyl alcohol (1,1,3-triphenylprop-2-yn-1-ol) 1a (0.35 mmol, 100 mg), 3-methylpentane-2,4-dione 2a (0.45 mmol, 52 mg), Ca(OTf)2 (11.9 mg, 10 mol-%) and Bu4NPF6 (7 mg, 5 mol-%) was refluxed in 1,2-dichloroethane (2 mL) at 90 °C for 2 h. After the complete conversion of compound 1a (monitored by TLC), 0.42 mmol (87 mg) of 1,3-diphenylprop-2-yn-1-ol 3a was added to the above reaction mixture and continued to reflux for 45 minutes. After the formation new spot on TLC, DABCO (3 equiv.) in aceto- nitrile (2 mL) was added to the reaction mixture and continued the reflux till the complete formation of the product (monitored by TLC). After completion of the reaction, the solvent was directly evaporated under reduced pressure to obtain the crude product. Then the crude product was purified by column chromatography (3–6 %, EtOAc in petroleum ether) to obtain the pure product 4a in 80 % yield.

II. Experimental procedure for the synthesis of fluoreno- [3,2-b]furan(6a): A mixture of tert-propargyl alcohol (1,1,3-triphen- ylprop-2-yn-1-ol) 1a (0.35 mmol, 100 mg), 3-methylpentane-2,4-di- one 2a (0.45 mmol, 52 mg), Ca(OTf)2 (12 mg, 10 mol-%) and Bu4NPF6 (7 mg, 5 mol-%) was refluxed in 1,2-DCE at 90 °C for 2 h. After the complete conversion of compound 1a (monitored by TLC), 0.42 mmol of sec-propargyl alcohol (ethyl 4-hydroxy-4-phenylbut-2- ynoate) 5a (86 mg) was added to the above reaction mixture and continued to reflux for 4–5 hours. After completion of the reaction (monitored by TLC), the solvent was directly concentrated under reduced pressure to isolate crude product which was purified by column chromatography (3–5 %, EtOAc in petroleum ether) to ob- tain the pure compound 6a in 75 % yield.

III. Experimental procedure for the synthesis of fluorenopyran (8a): A mixture of tert-propargyl alcohol (1,1,3-triphenylprop-2-yn- 1-ol) 1a (0.35 mmol, 100 mg), 3-methylpentane-2,4-dione 2a (0.45 mmol, 52 mg), Ca(OTf)2 (12 mg, 10 mol-%) and Bu4NPF6 (7 mg, 5 mol-%) was refluxed in 1,2-DCE at 90 °C for 2 h. After the complete conversion of compound 1a (monitored by TLC), 0.42 mmol of sec- propargyl alcohol 7a (79 mg) was added to the above reaction mixture and continued to reflux for 2–4 hours. After completion of the reaction (monitored by TLC), the solvent was directly concen- trated under reduced pressure to isolate crude product, which was purified by column chromatography (3–5 %, EtOAc in petroleum ether) to obtain the pure compound 8a in 76 % yield. IV. Experimental procedure for the synthesis of compound (10a):[25] A mixture of Cu(OTf)2 (10 mol-%), DDQ (0.27 mmol), tolu- ene (2 mL), phenylacetylene 9 (0.27 mmol) and fluoreno[3,2-b]furan 4a (0.18 mmol) was placed in a sealable tube. The tube was sealed and flushed with nitrogen; then the mixture was stirred at 120 °C for 24 hours. After completion of the reaction (monitor by TLC), the mixture was cooled to room temperature and flushed through a short column of silica gel with ethyl acetate. The solvent was re- moved under vacuum; the resultant dark purple crude was isolated and purified from by flash column chromatography to obtain the pure compound 10a in 50 % yield. 0.493 0.504 0.184 0.385 0.252 EurJOC European Journal of Organic Chemistry

Experimental procedure for the synthesis of (12):[26] A mixture of compound 4a (0.1 mmol), 4-methoxy phenol (11) (0.18 mmol), tricyclohexylphosphane (PCy3, 40 mol-%), and lithium chloride (5.0 equiv.) was taken into a sealed tube. The tube was evacuated and re-filled with nitrogen for 3 cycles then, anhydrous DMF (2.0 mL) and DBU (2.5 equiv.) were added. The tube was placed into a preheated oil bath at 100 °C for 14 h. After the completion of the reaction, the mixture was cooled to ambient temperature and di- luted with EtOAc and water. The organic layer was separated, and the aqueous layer was further extracted with EtOAc (ca. 10 mL × 3). The combined organic layers were dried with Na2SO4 and evapo- rated under reduced pressure. The crude product was purified by flash column chromatography on silica gel (60–120 mesh), using 6–7 %, EtOAc in pet ether to afford the pure product 12 in 55 % yield.
